<h1>@HI{{nomi}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@N{{}}@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}narazu}} ... @HI{{mo}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vplain{{}}@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}da}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}} can follow a noun and means that there is nothing other than  the thing stated: "only". In this usage
@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}} has the same meaning as <a href="grammar-particle-dake.html">@HI{{dake}}</a>, but it is used more in
writing than in the spoken language. @HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}} can be followed by <a href="grammar-particle-shika.html">@HI{{shika}}<a/>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{by*means*of^in*front}},kono@KJ{{large^study}}niha@KJ{{man^sex}}@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}}shika@KJ{{enter}}renakatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      In the past only men were able to enter this univeristy.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When the particle @HI{{de}} appears with @HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}}, there is a subtle difference in meaning according to whether @HI{{de}}
comes before or after @HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{day^book^word}}de@EM{{nomi}}@FG{{@KJ{{explanation^bright}}:setsumei}}@KJ{{exit^come}}ru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I can explain it only in Japanese. <em>(I cannot explain it in any other language)</em>
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{day^book^word}}@EM{{nomi}}de@FG{{@KJ{{explanation^bright}}:setsumei}}@KJ{{exit^come}}ru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I can explain it in Japanese alone. <em>(I don't need any other language other than Japanese to explain it)</em>
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}} can follow a verb in the informal form and means that there is nothing other than the action stated.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}hatada@KJ{{say}}waretakotosuru@EM{{nomi}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will do just what I was told to do.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
"A @HI{{@EM{{nomi}}narazu}}B@HI{{mo}}" is a form used to mean "not only ... but also ...".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{shixe-kusupia}}ha@KJ{{frolic^bend}}@EM{{nomi}}narazu@KJ{{poem}}motakusan@KJ{{write}}ita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Shakespeare wrote not only plays but many poems as well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The particles @HI{{ga}} and @HI{{wo}} are optional after @HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}}. Other particles may appear either before or after @HI{{@EM{{nomi}}}}.
</p>

